    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-05-06T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-05-06T17:00:00-05:00" n="502"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d502">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">561.311D1/34: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dawes</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-05-06T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >May 6, 1931—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>118. Your 119, April 24, 3 p.m. and subsequent correspondence in regard to the
                    Conference of Wheat Exporting Countries. Will the Conference assemble on May 18
                    as stated in Mr. Ferguson’s letter or on May 19 as stated in the official
                    invitation of the Canadian Government?</p>
                <p>Please inform Mr. Ferguson informally that the American representatives have been
                    designated as follows: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>The Honorable Samuel R. McKelvie, Member of the Federal Farm Board,
                            former Governor of Nebraska—Delegate.</p>
                        <p>Mr. Nils Andreas Olsen, Chief of the Bureau of Agricultural Economics of
                            the United States Department of Agriculture—Delegate.</p>
                        <p>Doctor Alonzo Englebert Taylor, Director of the Food Research Institute
                            of Leland Stanford University—Technical Adviser to the Delegation.</p>
                        <p>Mr. Raymond Edwin Cox, first Secretary of Embassy—Secretary to the
                            Delegation.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Please inform Cox of his designation and instruct him to attend all meetings of
                    the Conference, to keep the Department informed through you of any important
                    developments which may occur and to transmit any communications which the
                    Delegation may desire to send to the Department.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
